===Solution 1===

Notice that the bases of both triangles are diameters of the circle. Hence the ratio of the areas is just the ratio of the heights of the triangles, or <math> LaTex frac{CF}{CD}</math> (<math>F</math> is the foot of the [[perpendicular]] from <math>C</math> to <math>DE</math>).

Call the radius <math>r</math>. Then <math>AC =  LaTex frac 13(2r) =  LaTex frac 23r</math>, <math>CO =  LaTex frac 13r</math>. Using the [[Pythagorean Theorem]] in <math> LaTex triangle OCD</math>, we get <math> LaTex frac{1}{9}r^2 + CD^2 = r^2  LaTex Longrightarrow CD =  LaTex frac{2 LaTex sqrt{2}}3r</math>. 

Now we have to find <math>CF</math>. Notice <math> LaTex triangle OCD  LaTex sim  LaTex triangle OFC</math>, so we can write the [[proportion]]:

<div style="text-align:center;"><math> LaTex frac{OF}{OC} =  LaTex frac{OC}{OD}</math><br /><math> LaTex frac{OF}{ LaTex frac{1}{3}r} =  LaTex frac{ LaTex frac{1}{3}r}{r}</math><br /><math>OF =  LaTex frac 19r</math></div>

By the [[Pythagorean Theorem]] in <math> LaTex triangle OFC</math>, we have <math> LaTex left( LaTex frac{1}{9}r LaTex right)^2 + CF^2 =  LaTex left( LaTex frac{1}{3}r LaTex right)^2  LaTex Longrightarrow CF =  LaTex sqrt{ LaTex frac{8}{81}r^2} =  LaTex frac{2 LaTex sqrt{2}}{9}r</math>.

Our answer is <math> LaTex frac{CF}{CD} =  LaTex frac{ LaTex frac{2 LaTex sqrt{2}}{9}r}{ LaTex frac{2 LaTex sqrt{2}}{3}r} =  LaTex frac 13  LaTex Longrightarrow  LaTex mathrm{(C)}</math>.

